Introduction¶

The goal of this document is to display the progress towards the analysis of the data for the estimation of the number of vaccination and the number of children to vaccinate.

Data¶

In that section, we will present the different data sources used in the analysis.

As most of the data related to the Penta 1 vaccination start in 2021 in the DHIS2, this will be the starting date for most of the analysis.

As national subdivision change over time, we will present the data with their corresponding admin1 level, but then we will use the smallest subdivision whne combining the data.

The data for Penta 1 vaccination and Penta 1 coverage are extracted from the DHIS2.

Corrected Penta1 Coverage¶

This data will be updated as we progress towards an efficient method of estimation of the Penta1 coverage and Penta1 vaccinations.

For now, as a first step, we proposed a first methode of correction: carrying over the unvaccinated population of the previous months.
The hypothesis is that unvaccinated children from the precedent month do not vanish and are still unvaccinated during the next month.

Data Analysis¶

Relation between variables¶

Correlation between Penta1 vaccinations and stock at n-1: 0.1928597106168343

There is obviously a link between the end of month stock and the number of vaccination the next month, but the relation is not linear as the correlation is 0.37 (from a maximum of 1).
A big stock of vaccine in a month is often followed by a high number of vaccination the following month, but that's only the case for when the stock is big enough. Small variation in the stock does not translate into a change in the number of vaccination.

Correlation between the number of vaccinations and number of Political Violence Events¶

Correlation between Penta1 vaccinations and number of Events (conflict): 0.24511468792244107

There is a really weak link between the number of Events and the number of vaccination.
By looking at the graph, it seems that sometimes, the number of Events and the number of vaccinations are linked.
This could be due of the difference in where the events happen or something similar.

We will take a look at the correlation between Penta1 vaccinations and number of Events in each admin1.

Forecasting¶

The goal is to predict the number of Penta1 vaccinations in the future.
We will explore two strategies: a prediction at a national level and a prediction at a subnational level.

National level¶

To simulate a real life scenario, we will split the data into a train and a test set.

We will make prediction using data from 2021 to 2023, and we will be using data from 2023 to 2024 to optimize the prediction.
Finally, we will evaluate the final models using the data from 2024 to 2025.

Training dates   : 2021-01-01 00:00:00 --- 2023-01-01 00:00:00  (n=25)
Validation dates : 2023-01-01 00:00:00 --- 2024-01-01 00:00:00  (n=13)
Test dates       : 2024-01-01 00:00:00 --- 2025-07-01 00:00:00  (n=19)

Seasonality¶

Seasonal plots are a useful tool for identifying seasonal patterns and trends in a time series.

We will check for a monthly seasonality in the data.

Out[354]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Vaccinations per month (2021-2025)')

Number of vaccination seems to have low fluctuation in March, June, and September.
Number of vaccination seems to have high fluctuation in January, July, October and November.
Highest number of vaccination is in October, lowest number of vaccination is in Mai.

It seems there is monthly seasonality in the data: the peak number of vaccination is between Mai and June and between November and December.
Lowest number of vaccination will be between February and April.

Autocorrelation¶

Autocorrelation is a measure of the correlation between a time series and its own lagged values.

In simple terms, it measures the relation between the current value and the value in the past.

There is also a medium positive relation between the vaccination in a month and the corresponding vaccination in the precedent year.

Baseline model¶

We will use a simple model to predict the number of vaccination in the future.
This will be a baseline model and will be use to evaluate if more complex models are better.

We will use a Seasonal Naive Forecasting model, which is simply returning the value observed in the same period of the previous season (in our case, the same month, but in the previous year).
